text: I'll give this a shot, but I'm not looking sure if I feel ok with this. I can understand using a video game, because of the whole wanting to suck the four kids into the jungle bit couldn't be done with a board game. What I can't really understand is why make this a comedy? The original was actually very serious in tone, which made it more interesting. text: Its true, in this day and age the majority of people only play video games now. Board games what are those? Sadly its a lost hobby of sorts that needs to be discovered again. I bet most of you who are reading this right now believe that the only kind of board games that exist are Sorry, Trouble, Risk and Monopoly to name a few. That isn't the case. Board games are still very much alive and active. I know this because I collect board games as a hobby. There's an actual community of people who play board games instead of video games. Every year new board games are released just like video games. Here's what kind of board games that are out there today: having a virus spread across the world while you try to contain it as much as possible before it kills everyone. Its called Pandemic. Look it up if you don't believe me. I know this comment came out of left field, I was just reading some of the comments below talking about how people don't play board games anymore, which isn't true. I wanted to open up some minds to a different kind of gaming world. You might be surprised and become obsessed like me. :)

text: This is not even a remake, its a new, original movie that they have slapped the "Jumanji" name on to ensure sales. Similar to what they have done with 21 Jump st ect.   I think it looks like a good movie, but its so different, I am not even able to compare it to the original. One is a Drama, one is a Comedy  Jumanji was about a a body stuck in a board game for 20 years, coming back, re-adjusting  and bringing the game with him. This is a a bunch of teenagers stuck in a video game and become their avatars, for what I assume will not even be more than a Month  When you compare the blurbs, it is not even close to an actual remake. Which I think is a good thing in my opinion. Cant improve on perfection!

text: I would have just preferred the board game and not this video game crap. I mean in the original, they did already establish that the board game has been found by countless others throughout history, so the idea of stumbling across the same one isn't that farfetched. The original had a mystical element to it. If Hollywood figured people would think a board game would be outdated, I believe on the contrary that in a world smothered by technology, a board game is almost like a breathe of fresh air. This is such a missed opportunity to craft a brilliant family adventure film. It's clearly just pandering to a younger dumber demographic with stupid 2017 humour. What an insult to Robin's memory

text: While I do think Jack Black is going to be hilarious playing as some prom queen teenage drama queen, I am a bit disappointed that they ended up making Jumanji into a video game just to cater to the younger audiences and make them get sucked into it. Like, the board game thing was actually a really cool concept that has been copied before (Zathura anyone?). I also think have Dwayne, and Kevin in a movie together again. Plus with Jack Black, I think it will be pretty funny. But giving them special powers because they're in a video game? I understand it, but the thrill of the original was that you didn't have special powers. It was about the wild coming out to you. I think this movie is going to be funny, but it's going to take away the thrill and what was actually terrifying about Jumanji. Oh well. All good things come to an end.

text: For everyone saying something along the lines of, "stop complaining haters," many of the greats of our time, such as Steven Spielberg and Martin Scorsese, are now openly ridiculing and lamenting about how people no longer watching "boring" classics retards  people's ability to objectively know the difference between a movie of substance and a movie of crap. People literally no longer understand the deeper language of film. That's what happens when quality is seen as subjective, cheap comedy wins the day, and empty entertainment subverts thought provoking greatness.   If you still think  this movie looks great and I'm the one full of crap, feel free to look up Bruckheimer's comments about how the reading level of movies keeps going lower and lower every year or how Tarantino complains about how studios no longer want to spend time shooting with one camera, rather they just want to do one take with as many cameras as possible to be as cheap as possible without spending the time to fully think out shots, the likes of which was crucial to the greatness of Hitchcock and Tarantino's - all of this is really happening and it's really a problem.   While this is only a trailer for the film, this looks more like a Scary Movie spoof than a movie of substance. Oh well, I'll just have to watch the original. It certainly wasn't a Kubrick film, but it had heart and a decent level of competency not to mention Robin Williams was a rather strong actor, especially compared to any role the rock has played. Yes, he's a likable guy, but he is not a gifted actor. Take away all his fans and he wouldn't be getting all the roles he does.  Thanks for reading!

text: I see a lot of hate in the comment section because it isn't the original. I see a lot of hate because it is not a board game being used. May I ask, just for a brief consideration based on levelheaded thinking, why it is bad that they are trying new stuff with Classics? It doesn't change or ruin the original movie in anyway, and it could very well come out as a great summer flick that surprises all of you. I'm not saying you have to love it based on the trailers, but giving it a chance isn't exactly a bad thing.   Just so I don't get tons of hate for being young and into video games, I loved the original movie and Robin Williams is a legend. Board games are extremely fun and creative, but not everyone is into them nowadays, so i can see the appeal of changing the format of the game to test the waters. I just want to keep an open mind about this, and hope it brings a similar message and feeling of wonderment as the first in a new, different package.

text: Stuck in a video game, plenty of that kind made in Japan. Jumanji was this mysterious yet also terrifying board game.  The kids and Robin Williams was themselves, no action hey I'm a super good fighter star. They were in the real world, at the same time the game's fantasy world clashed by reality. Creating a lot of trouble and consequences. It was interresting and fun, also relateable as you also would've been scared playing that when you were a child. This sensation of wondering what happens next was just the best.  This looks like an action/comedy that was not necessary to have the Jumanji name. It could had been an own movie as it doesn't look anything like it.

text: Seriously... to be fair... this could be a good movie given a REALLY bad trailer. (Seems to be a thing these days.) It makes it look so forced and generic. Which the movie very well might be.   That said. I already know I won't like the movie due to childhood bias and am insulted that it's a video game. I've been waiting for a horror movie or something with an old game console as it's focus, but Jumanji???? What?? Give me the damned board game! I've been waiting years for that! I think I'd have been more fine if it had been a Zathura remake. It would be more fitting.   I'm not a fan of the rock in movies like this... I was not impressed with him in comedic sets. This just steels the idea.... fancy effects and hokey actors are no replacement for an original formula, and safe to say, I'm gonna wait for this to air on TV rather than blow money on this.
